- `isInterpreterLikeAllowlistPattern` only recognizes a fixed set of unversioned interpreter names via exact string membership. For versioned binaries like `python3.14`, it returns `false`, so the whole strictInlineEval persistence-prevention block is skipped and `addAllowAlwaysPattern(...)` runs unconditionally.

## Codebase Inconsistency
`src/infra/exec-safe-bin-runtime-policy.ts` already solves the same “is this an interpreter?” question using regexes that match versioned names (e.g. `python3.12`, `node20`, `ruby3.2`), but `strictInlineEval` uses only exact name matching, leading to false negatives for versioned interpreters.

# Exploit Scenario
