# Explanation
Doctor and runtime use different profile resolution logic:
- Runtime uses `resolveSafeBinProfiles`, which merges `SAFE_BIN_PROFILES` with user overrides, so a bin like `grep` is considered profiled even when the user has no `safeBinProfiles.grep` entry.
- Doctor uses `resolveMergedSafeBinProfileFixtures`, which merges only user fixtures and omits `SAFE_BIN_PROFILES`, so doctor incorrectly reports built-in bins as missing a profile.

Because user profiles override built-ins, the `{}` scaffold that doctor writes for these bins replaces built-in constraints with an empty profile (e.g., `grep` denied flags become `[]`, other limits become unset), making the effective runtime policy less restrictive.

## Codebase Inconsistency
Runtime determines unprofiled bins based on the fully-resolved profiles (including built-ins), but doctor determines missing profiles using fixtures-only profiles. With the same input (`safeBins: ["grep"]` and no user profile), runtime reports no unprofiled bins while doctor flags `missingProfile`.

