  body = undefined;
  headers = new Headers(headers);
  headers.delete("content-type");
  headers.delete("content-length");
}
```

# Explanation
For cross-origin redirects, the transport always strips the `Authorization` header, indicating it treats cross-origin redirects as a security boundary. However, it only drops the request body for 301/302/303 (by switching the method to `GET`). For 307/308, the HTTP semantics preserve the original method and body, and the transport does not apply any additional logic to drop the body, so sensitive POST/PUT payloads can be forwarded to a different origin.

## Codebase Inconsistency
The core SSRF guard (`src/infra/net/fetch-guard.ts`) explicitly drops request bodies for non-GET/HEAD cross-origin redirects (including 307/308) unless an explicit opt-in is set:

```typescript
// src/infra/net/fetch-guard.ts
function rewriteRedirectInitForCrossOrigin(params: {
  init?: RequestInit;
  allowUnsafeReplay: boolean;
}): RequestInit | undefined {
  if (!init || allowUnsafeReplay) return init;

  const currentMethod = init.method?.toUpperCase() ?? "GET";
  if (currentMethod === "GET" || currentMethod === "HEAD") return init;

  return {
    ...init,
    body: undefined,
    headers: dropBodyHeaders(init.headers),
  };
}
```

# Exploit Scenario
1. User configures homeserver `https://matrix.example.com`.
2. Attacker controls/compromises the homeserver (or can tamper with responses).
3. Homeserver returns an HTTP 307/308 redirect for a sensitive endpoint (e.g. `/_matrix/client/v3/login`) to `https://attacker.com/capture`.
4. Matrix transport strips `Authorization` but forwards the original POST body to the new origin.
5. Attacker captures sensitive data from the forwarded body (e.g., password, message content, device keys).

# Recommended Fix
Drop request bodies (and body-related headers) for cross-origin redirects on non-GET/HEAD methods, including 307/308, mirroring the core SSRF guard behavior:

```typescript
if (nextUrl.origin !== currentUrl.origin) {
  headers = new Headers(headers);
  headers.delete("authorization");

  if (method !== "GET" && method !== "HEAD") {
    body = undefined;
    headers.delete("content-type");
    headers.delete("content-length");
  }
}
```

# History
This bug was introduced in commit f62be0ddcf. This commit added comprehensive SSRF protections (DNS pinning, cross-protocol blocking, auth header stripping) to Matrix's redirect handling, but overlooked stripping request bodies for 307/308 cross-origin redirects.

