# Summary
- **Context**: The Matrix transport layer implements SSRF protection for Matrix API requests, including DNS pinning, cross-protocol blocking, and auth header stripping on cross-origin redirects.
- **Bug**: Request bodies are preserved on cross-origin 307/308 redirects while auth headers are stripped - an inconsistent security posture that leaks sensitive data to untrusted origins.
- **Actual vs. expected**: The Matrix transport strips Authorization headers on cross-origin redirects (for all status codes) but does NOT strip request bodies for 307/308. The core SSRF guard strips both.
- **Impact**: An attacker who can control or compromise the homeserver can capture sensitive request bodies (messages, passwords, cryptographic keys) by returning a 307/308 redirect to a cross-origin server.

# Code with bug
```typescript
// extensions/matrix/src/matrix/sdk/transport.ts:189-205

if (nextUrl.origin !== currentUrl.origin) {
  headers = new Headers(headers);
  headers.delete("authorization");
  // BUG: Body is NOT stripped for 307/308, only for 301/302/303 below
}

if (
  response.status === 303 ||
  ((response.status === 301 || response.status === 302) &&
    method !== "GET" &&
    method !== "HEAD")
) {
  method = "GET";
  body = undefined;
  headers = new Headers(headers);
  headers.delete("content-type");
  headers.delete("content-length");
}
```

The code handles 301/302/303 redirects correctly by converting to GET and dropping the body. However, for 307/308 redirects, there is **no body stripping on cross-origin redirects** - the body is preserved and forwarded to the new origin, even though the Authorization header WAS stripped.

# Evidence

## Evidence 1: Matrix Transport Already Implements SSRF Protection

The Matrix transport implements multiple SSRF protection mechanisms, proving it is designed for adversarial scenarios:

```typescript
// extensions/matrix/src/matrix/sdk/transport.ts:115-145
async function fetchWithMatrixGuardedRedirects(params: {
  // ...
  ssrfPolicy?: SsrFPolicy;  // SSRF policy is configurable
}) {
  // ...
  const pinned = await resolvePinnedHostnameWithPolicy(currentUrl.hostname, {
    policy: params.ssrfPolicy,
  });
  dispatcher = createPinnedDispatcher(pinned, params.dispatcherPolicy, params.ssrfPolicy);
  // ...
}
```

The transport also:
- Blocks cross-protocol redirects (HTTP → HTTPS and vice versa)
- Detects redirect loops
- Limits redirect count (max 5)
- Strips Authorization headers on cross-origin redirects

This demonstrates the transport IS designed to handle security risks, not just trusted homeserver communication.

## Evidence 2: Inconsistency Between Auth Header Stripping and Body Handling

The code explicitly strips Authorization headers on cross-origin redirects for **ALL** redirect status codes (including 307/308):

```typescript
// transport.ts:189-192
if (nextUrl.origin !== currentUrl.origin) {
  headers = new Headers(headers);
  headers.delete("authorization");  // Stripped for 307/308 too!
}
```

If the design were "trust the homeserver completely", auth headers would NOT be stripped. The fact that they ARE stripped proves the code considers cross-origin redirect security risks - but body handling was overlooked.

## Evidence 3: Core SSRF Guard Has Explicit Opt-In for Body Replay

The core SSRF guard in `src/infra/net/fetch-guard.ts` has an `allowCrossOriginUnsafeRedirectReplay` parameter:

```typescript
// src/infra/net/fetch-guard.ts:44-45
allowCrossOriginUnsafeRedirectReplay?: boolean;

// src/infra/net/fetch-guard.ts:244-263
function rewriteRedirectInitForCrossOrigin(params: {
  init?: RequestInit;
  allowUnsafeReplay: boolean;
}): RequestInit | undefined {
  if (!init || allowUnsafeReplay) return init;  // Opt-in required for body replay

  const currentMethod = init.method?.toUpperCase() ?? "GET";
  if (currentMethod === "GET" || currentMethod === "HEAD") return init;

  return {
    ...init,
    body: undefined,
    headers: dropBodyHeaders(init.headers),
  };
}
```

The default is `false` - body replay is NOT allowed without explicit opt-in. The Matrix transport has no such opt-in mechanism; it always allows body replay.

## Evidence 4: Core Tests Explicitly Protect Against 307/308 Body Leakage

From `src/infra/net/fetch-guard.ssrf.test.ts:783-816`:

```typescript
