// Startup will fail closed if no resolved browser auth is available.
```

This comment says "SecretRef-style" - which includes BOTH forms:
- Object form: `{ source: "env", provider: "default", id: "TOKEN" }`
- Env-template form: `"${TOKEN}"` (recognized by `coerceSecretRef`)

The function name says "NonString" but the comment says "SecretRef-style". When there's a mismatch between name and documented intent, the documented intent should win. The name may reflect the implementation shortcut, not the correct behavior.

## 5. Both SecretRef forms are FIRST-CLASS features throughout the codebase

The `coerceSecretRef` function in `src/config/types.secrets.ts:80-101` handles BOTH forms EQUALLY:

```typescript
export function coerceSecretRef(value: unknown, defaults?: SecretDefaults): SecretRef | null {
  if (isSecretRef(value)) {
    return value;  // Object form
  }
  // ... legacy handling ...
  const envTemplate = parseEnvTemplateSecretRef(value, defaults?.env);
  if (envTemplate) {
    return envTemplate;  // Env-template form - FIRST CLASS, not legacy
  }
  return null;
}
```

There is NO "legacy" marker or compatibility flag for env-template. Both forms are treated identically. This is used in 20+ places throughout the codebase to detect SecretRefs. The check in `control-auth.ts` is the ONLY place that uses `typeof !== "string"` instead.

